The card will have a number of stars at the top from one to five, signifying their rarity - the more stars, the rarer the Servant is. The card's borders will either be brown for common (1-2 stars), silver for rare (3 stars), and gold for super rare (4-5 stars). Below the character's portrait will be their class name and True Name, and then the class icon. On the bottom left corner will be their ATK value, while the bottom right corner will have their HP value.

title: telstar_18
body:
The official [[soccer ball]] being used in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] being held in Russia. Its design pays homage to the original [[Telstar]] soccer ball which has become the representative soccer ball. Telstar 18's design differs from the Telstar in the design of its "black" panels that look like pixellated gray oval trajectories. Also, unlike the Telstar and like the more recent soccer ball designs material-wise, the Telstar 18's panels are glued together rather than stitched.

Since the round of 16, Telstar Mechta (Мечта, meaning "dream" or "ambition"), a version of Telstar 18 with red features, made its appearance.

title: red_fox_(kemono_friends)
body:
A [i][[Kemono Friends]][/i] character. She is one of many "Friends" in Japari Park.

The Red Fox ([i]Vulpes vulpes[/i]) is the largest of the true foxes and is widespread over all of the northern hemisphere. Thus, it has many [[silver_fox_(kemono_friends)|variants]] and [[ezo_red_fox_(kemono_friends)|subspecies]]. Being widespead, it has spawned [[kyuubi_(kemono_friends)|many]] [[oinari-sama_(kemono_friends)|legends]] about it throughout the world.

Red Fox (the Friend) is dressed similarly to a blazer-less [[ezo_red_fox_(kemono_friends)|Ezo Red Fox]], with a short-sleeved button-up shirt with a white chest and orange sleeves. She also wears a gray skirt and black socks (instead of the other foxes' pantyhose). She also wears black elbow gloves (which the others are also implied to wear). She has the same hairdo as Ezo Red Fox but can be distinguished from her with her deep red hair instead of Ezo's blonde.

title: hachisuka_kotetsu
body:
Personification of the Hachisuka Kotetsu sword. Uchigatana class. Historically, the sword was the treasure of the Hachisuka Clan.

In [i][[Touken Ranbu]][/i], Hachisuka has a strong aversion to the "counterfeit" Kotetsu swords, including [[Nagasone Kotetsu]]. He takes pride in the fact that he and his self proclaimed brother [[Urashima Kotetsu]] are the real deal. In addition to this he's also a bit of a narcissist, seen in his fieldwork quote. Despite all of these negative qualities, he still secretly has respect for Nagasone, but doesn't want to admit it.

He's one of the five swords the player can choose when starting the game, alongside [[Kashuu Kiyomitsu]], [[Yamanbagiri Kunihiro]], [[Mutsu-no-Kami Yoshiyuki]], and [[Kasen Kanesada]].

He has long [[purple hair]] and [[blue eyes]], with [[white gloves]], a [[full armor|full]] [[gold armor|golden]] [[armor]] set, and golden [[armored boots]]. In his casual mode he has a [[high ponytail]] coupled with a golden [[kimono]] and [[haori]] with golden [[sandals]]. The over saturation of gold on his person references the fact that the ornate mountings of the original sword (in addition to the inscription on the sword) are colored gold. Because of this, fans see more than a [[look-alike|passing resemblance]] to him and [[Aries Muu]].

Seiyuu is Kazuyuki Okitsu. Character designer is [[Arai Teruko]].

title: tengai_makyou
body:
Literally 'Devil's World Far from Heaven' (or possibly just 'Magic World Outside of Heaven'), is an RPG series very popular in Japan and Taiwan but virtually unknown in other regions. Tengai Makyou spans four official games and various side games, all of them parodying Japan in the fictional land 'Jipang'. The games usually humorize Western society's misconceptions about Japan, however [i]The Apocalypse IV[/i] instead parodies Japanese misconceptions about America, and [i]Oriental Blue[/i] is not really humor based.

Often known as Far East of Eden, however this is technically a sub-series within Tengai Makyou, as well as the name of a in-universe source material that the series is based on. However, the cancelled releases of Tengai Makyou all used [i]Far East of Eden[/i] as the planned localized name. Only one game, [i]Kabuki Klash[/i] (Shin Den), was released in English.

The series has similarities with [[Sakura Taisen]] as both have the same creator, and Red Entertainment has worked on both series.

title: a-1_skyraider
body:
The Douglas A-1 Skyraider was an American single-seat attack aircraft. It was originally designed during World War II to replace earlier dive bombers such as the [[SB2C Helldiver]] and torpedo bombers such as the TBF Avenger.

A piston-powered, propeller-driven aircraft during the late-40s where designers were focusing on jet aircraft, it had much longer endurance than the jet fighters of its era. 

Though it entered too late to serve in World War II, it first entered combat during the Korean War. Subsequently, its advantage of long endurance allowed it to serve close air support during the Vietnam War.

It was known for "dropping a toilet":http://www.midwaysailor.com/midwayva25bomb/ in October 1965 to highlight the six millionth pound of ordnance dropped.

The aircraft was designed by Ed Heinemann who earlier designed the [[SBD Dauntless]]. He would subsequently design the [[A-4 Skyhawk]].

body:
Oldrin Zevon is the female protagonist of [i][[Code Geass]][/i] spin-off [i][[Code Geass: Oz the Reflection]][/i]. 

She serves as the head knight of the Britannian Military's anti-terrorism unit, the "Glinda Knights", which was formed to counter the terrorism that began to occur in greater frequency after the Black Rebellion ended in Area 11. She is good friends with the group's leader, 88th Imperial Princess [[Marrybel mel Britannia]], whom Oldrin has known since childhood. She also pilots a [[lancelot (code geass)|Lancelot]] variant, the Lancelot Grail.

Oldrin has a twin brother, a young man named [[Orpheus Zevon]].

title: kaolla_su
body:
Kaolla Su is an eighth grade foreign exchange student who boards at the Hinata House. She goes to the same school as Shinobu Maehara. 

Liking to keep her origins a secret, it was initially thought that she was from India, or possibly even Australia. However, it was later revealed that she was actually a royal princess from the Kingdom of Molmol, an island nation in the Pacific. 

Possessing an Indian appearance, Kaolla is often barefoot and dressed in nothing else except her school uniform. But she does wear sneakers on some occasions. She is extremely hyperactive, usually hugging (or, in Keitaro's case, kicking) someone, trying to eat something, especially bananas and/or Tama, or inventing some potentially dangerous new device. She also has a tendency to snuggle against a person while she is sleeping and usually crushes them while doing it.

Due to the "azuki" in his name, Azuki Nagamitsu is portrayed as a man who has sweetness embedded in his very core. He is a kind, fatherly man who puts the wellbeing of the childlike tantous before his own. He is also skilled at making sweets; for this reason, fans like to have the sweets-loving [[Houchou Toushirou]] approach him for food due to his parental aura.

It was first released in Japan on Saturday, November 1, 1986, and then was distributed to Europe, Australia and the United States in 1987.

It was arguably the most widely known game in the Alex Kidd series by [[SEGA]] Corporation, due to it being built internally into most Master System II consoles as an included bundled title. title: dlsite.com_15_year_anniversary_contest
body:
A mascot character contest held on Nico Nico Seiga for the 15 year anniversary of "DLsite.com":http://www.dlsite.com 

The theme was a "Home Security 'Girl'" (自宅警備 "娘"). This is a play on the slang term "Home Security Guard" (自宅警備員 [jitaku keibi'in], sometimes abbreviated as JK). The term means something like [[NEET]]. It's used for people that, instead of going to work or school, are at home all day. The joke is that they're not NEETs, they're home security guards. It's simply their job to stay home all day and "guard" it. See "here":http://bangin.wordpress.com/2008/10/07/%E8%87%AA%E5%AE%85%E8%AD%A6%E5%82%99%E5%93%A1jitaku-keibiin/ for more info on the term. 


h4. Winners and Prizes

body:
The original version of [[Chris Jericho]]'s [[Walls of Jericho]] signature move. 

Truly the more painful and more brutal version of the Walls of Jericho, this is also a higher-angle [[boston crab]] but with the addition of the wrestler using a single knee to add additional pressure by pressing it into the opponent's back or on the back of the opponent's neck.
Chris Jericho rarely uses the Liontamer anymore because it is very difficult to perform on larger opponents and the legit danger this move may cause if applied incorrectly.

[[WWE]] NXT wrestler Roderick Strong also uses this [[submission hold]] which he calls the [i]Strong Hold[/i]. This version focuses more on the lower back of the opponent, which fits to his "Messiah of the Backbreaker" nickname.

title: isabella_valentine
body:
An anti-heroine character from [[Namco]]'s [[Soulcalibur]] series of fighting games, also known as Ivy for short. 

A reclusive English noblewoman and alchemist, Ivy suffers from a blood curse that ties her to the corruptive weapon [[Soul Edge (weapon)|Soul Edge]], and she intends to find a way to break that curse. Visually, she is famed for her [[short hair|short]], [[white hair|white]]/[[silver hair|silver]] hair, her [[large breasts]], and her revealing leather outfit she wears into battle that varies with each game. Her weapon of choice is a [[whip sword]] of her own design that can freely expand and contract between a regular sword and the extended whip-sword form, a weapon that moves according to her will. She is known to show dominant, almost sadist, tendencies while fighting, including stepping on her enemies on the ground and turning them into a [[human chair|chair]] as part of one of her throws.

Ivy's biological father is the dread pirate [[Cervantes de Leon]] and the reason for her blood curse.

title: gustav_munchausen
body:
Gustav Munchausen (Occasionally, and erroneously, spelled 'Gustab'), is a character from [[The King of Fighters]].

Gustav was introduced in the GBA spinoff game [[the_king_of_fighters_ex2|The King of Fighters EX2: Neo Blood]], where he hosted said game's tournament. Lusting for supernatural powers, despite being a multimillionaire already, Gustav channels the spirit of [[Goenitz]] into Sinobu Amou, the game's boss character, for use as his puppet. After Sinobu is defeated by the player, Gustav disappears without any explanation.

Gustav is much more infamously known due to his inclusion as the final boss of the [[M.U.G.E.N]]-developed King of Fighters fangame [i]The King of Fighters Memorial[/i]. Story-wise, Gustav hosts another King of Fighters tournament to get revenge on [[kusanagi_kyou|Kyo Kusanagi]] and [[yagami_iori|Iori Yagami]] for foiling his plans in EX2, requesting the help of his close assistant [[Psyqhical]]. With his monetary powers, Gustav manages to create clones of many major boss characters from the King of Fighters series, including [[Rugal Bernstein]], [[Krizalid]], [[zero_(kof)|both versions]] [[Original Zero|of Zero]], [[igniz_(kof)|Igniz]], and even Kyo and Iori themselves.

Gustav's appearance in [I]Memorial[/i] is heavily based off of [[oswald_(kof)|Oswald]]'s sprite sheet, therefore giving him very overdramatic poses. In-game, he is absurdly overpowered; being able to make use of infinite priority normals and projectiles, and full screen special attacks.

[[Hei Meiling]] is an edit of him.

title: muff
body:
A muff is a fashion accessory for outdoors usually made of a cylinder of fur or fabric with both ends open for keeping the hands warm. It was introduced to women's fashion in the 16th century and was popular with both men and women in the 17th and 18th centuries. By the early 20th century, muffs were used in England only by women. It is also reported that the fashion largely fell out of style in the 19th century.

It briefly returned in the late 1940s and 1950s, and was also developed as a motorcycle accessory for attachment as rider-protection and comfort during the cooler months.
